objects.name: Boggy Serpens
objects.description: Boggy Serpens aka MuddyWater is a threat group that has primarily targeted Middle Eastern nations, and has also targeted European and North American nations. The group's victims are mainly in the telecommunications, government (IT services), and oil sectors. Activity from this group was previously linked to FIN7, but the group is believed to be a distinct group possibly motivated by espionage.

objects.name: Middle East Attacks Campaign
objects.description: Boggy Serpens attacks are primarily against Middle Eastern nations. However, Unit 42 has also observed attacks against surrounding nations and beyond, including targets in India and the USA. Boggy Serpens attacks are characterized by the use of a slowly evolving PowerShell-based first stage backdoor called  “POWERSTATS”. Despite broad scrutiny and reports on Boggy Serpens attacks, the activity continues with only incremental changes to the tools and techniques.

objects.name: BlackWater Campaign
objects.description: Cisco Talos assesses with moderate confidence that a campaign recently discovered called "BlackWater" is associated with suspected persistent threat actor Boggy Serpens. Newly associated samples from April 2019 indicate attackers have added three distinct steps to their operations, allowing them to bypass certain security controls and suggesting that Boggy Serpens's tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) have evolved to evade detection. If successful, this campaign would install a PowerShell-based backdoor onto the victim's machine, giving the threat actors remote access. While this activity indicates the threat actor is taking steps to improve its operational security and avoid endpoint detection, the underlying code remains unchanged.

Newly associated samples from April 2019 indicate attackers have added three distinct steps to their operations, allowing them to bypass certain security controls and suggesting that Boggy Serpens's tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) have evolved to evade detection. If successful, this campaign would install a PowerShell-based backdoor onto the victim's machine, giving the threat actors remote access. While this activity indicates the threat actor is taking steps to improve its operational security and avoid endpoint detection, the underlying code remains unchanged.

objects.name: laZagne
objects.description: The LaZagne project is an open source application used to retrieve lots of passwords stored on a local computer. Each software stores its passwords using different techniques (plaintext, APIs, custom algorithms, databases, etc.). This tool has been developed for the purpose of finding these passwords for the most commonly-used software.

objects.name: POWERSTATS
objects.description: POWERSTATS is a PowerShell based backdoor used in targeted attacks. The backdoor supports simple commands and exfiltrating basic system information to the attacker.
